column30: See Library text document. / To make the burnup, specific power, and total time self-consistent, put the capacity factor at 0.6066 = 965 x 3 W-day/kg / 83.60 / 365.25 = 31.60 years / 52.1 = 0.6066.  To get to 99% FIMA takes 52 years (assuming 100% plant availability), but the plant operates at nominal power only for 30 years (the last ~20 years operates below nominal power but still 100% availability) / A majority of the neutrons in the blanket are fission-born rather than fusion-born. Most of the fissions occur at a normal fission spectrum so the fast library is applicable. / Another unique aspect of this calculation is that the fissionable material is taken to 99% burnup.  This means that fission products have more opportunity to subsequently react with neutrons via (n,γ) and (n,2n) reactions than lower burnup cases.
column31: See library documentation.  Single unit cell used with adjusted graphite volume to best match average spectrum in whole core.
column33: Core average void fraction of 40% to account for the change in void fraction across the core.  This makes it representative of a core average calculation.
